<h1>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe a customary action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{every^morning}} @KT{{jogingu}}wo shi<strong>te imasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I jog every morning.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe a state which is the result of the action expressed
by the verb. If the verb describes an action that can be repeated or continued,
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> expresses the continuation of that action. Otherwise if the
verb expresses a momentary action, <strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> expresses the idea
that the action happened and the resulting state continues. Verbs used in this construction
are intransitive ones.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{window}}ga @KJ{{proportion}}re<strong>te imasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The window is broken.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{electricity^spirit}}ga tsui<strong>te imasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The light is on.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KJ{{tie^marriage}}shite imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm married.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe an action that is in progress.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha @KJ{{now electricity^tale}}wo kakete imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller is making a phone call now.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe an action that is habitual.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{su-pa-}}de @KT{{firumu}}wo @KJ{{sell}}tte imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Supermarkets sell films.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When the verb is one of motion, such as @HI{{kuru}} or @HI{{kaeru}}, 
the meaning is to have performed the motion and its results persist. 
For example, @HI{{itte iru}} means to have gone somewhere and still be there.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{sumu}} requires this sentence pattern if the sentence expresses a continuing state.
</p>

<p>
Verbs such as @HI{{iu}} and @HI{{omou}} require this sentence pattern if the subject is the
third person and the sentence expresses a present state.
</p>

